1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ESTABLISH AN INTERSTATE COMPACT FOR THE LICENSURE OF THE
3 PRACTICE OF MEDICINE AND TO CREATE A PROCESS FOR INTERNATIONAL
4 PHYSICIAN EMPLOYEE LICENSE.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new Article
7 to read:
8 "Article 1O.
9 "Interstate Medical Licensure Compact.
10 "§ 90-21.160. Short title.
11 This Article shall be known as the "Interstate Medical Licensure Compact."
12 "§ 90-21.161. Purpose.
13 (a) The purpose of this Article is to strengthen access to health care, and, in recognition
14 of the advances in the delivery of health care, the member states of the Interstate Medical
15 Licensure Compact (Compact) have allied in common purpose to develop a comprehensive
16 process that complements the existing licensing and regulatory authority of state medical boards
17 and to provide a streamlined process that allows physicians to become licensed in multiple states,
18 thereby enhancing the portability of a medical license and ensuring the safety of patients.
19 (b) The Interstate Medical Licensure Compact creates another pathway for licensure and
20 does not otherwise change a state's existing medical practice act or provisions. The Compact
21 adopts the prevailing standard for licensure and affirms that the practice of medicine occurs
22 where the patient is located at the time of the physician-patient encounter and, therefore, requires
23 the physician to be under the jurisdiction of the state medical board where the patient is located.
24 State medical boards that participate in the Compact retain the jurisdiction to impose an adverse
25 action against a license to practice medicine in that state issued to a physician through the
26 procedures of the Compact.
27 "§ 90-21.162. Definitions.
28 The following definitions apply in this Article:
29 (1) Bylaws. – Bylaws established by the Interstate Commission pursuant to
30 G.S. 90-21.171.
31 (2) Commissioner. – The voting representative appointed by each member board
32 pursuant to G.S. 90-21.171.
33 (3) Conviction. – A finding by a court that an individual is guilty of a criminal
34 offense through adjudication, or entry of a plea of guilty or no contest to the
35 charge by the offender. Evidence of an entry of a conviction of a criminal
*S336-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 offense by a court shall be considered final for purposes of disciplinary action
2 by a member board.
3 (4) Expedited license. – A full and unrestricted medical license granted by a
4 member state to an eligible physician through the process set forth in the
5 Compact.
6 (5) Interstate Commission. – The Interstate Medical Licensure Compact
7 Commission created pursuant to G.S. 90-21.171.
8 (6) License. – The authorization by a member state for a physician to engage in
9 the practice of medicine, which would be unlawful without authorization.
10 (7) Medical practice act. – Laws and regulations governing the practice of
11 allopathic and osteopathic medicine within a member state.
12 (8) Member board. – A state agency in a member state that acts in the sovereign
13 interests of the state by protecting the public through licensure, regulation, and
14 education of physicians as directed by the state government.
15 (9) Member state. – A state that has enacted the Compact.
16 (10) Offense. – A felony, gross misdemeanor, or crime of moral turpitude.
17 (11) Physician. – Any person who meets all of the following qualifications:
18 a. Is a graduate of a medical school accredited by the Liaison Committee
19 on Medical Education, the Commission on Osteopathic College
20 Accreditation, or a medical school listed in the International Medical
21 Education Directory or its equivalent.
22 b. Has passed each component of the United States Medical Licensing
23 Examination (USMLE) or the Comprehensive Osteopathic Medical
24 Licensing Examination (COMLEX-USA) within three attempts, or
25 any of its predecessor examinations accepted by a state medical board
26 as an equivalent examination for licensure purposes.
27 c. Has successfully completed graduate medical education approved by
28 the Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education or the
29 American Osteopathic Association.
30 d. Holds specialty certification or a time-unlimited specialty certificate
31 recognized by the American Board of Medical Specialties or the
32 American Osteopathic Association's Bureau of Osteopathic
33 Specialists.
34 e. Possesses a full and unrestricted license to engage in the practice of
35 medicine issued by a member board.
36 f. Has never been convicted, received adjudication, deferred
37 adjudication, community supervision, or deferred disposition for any
38 offense by a court of appropriate jurisdiction.
39 g. Has never held a license authorizing the practice of medicine subjected
40 to discipline by a licensing agency in any state, federal, or foreign
41 jurisdiction, excluding any action related to nonpayment of fees
42 related to a license.
43 h. Has never had a controlled substance license or permit suspended or
44 revoked by a state or the United States Drug Enforcement
45 Administration.
46 i. Is not under active investigation by a licensing agency or law
47 enforcement authority in any state, federal, or foreign jurisdiction.
48 (12) Practice of medicine. – Clinical prevention, diagnosis, or treatment of human
49 disease, injury, or condition requiring a physician to obtain and maintain a
50 license in compliance with the medical practice act of a member state.
