30 SECTION 3. Article 1 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
31 a new section to read:
32 "§ 90-12.03. Internationally-trained physician employee license.
33 (a) The Board may issue an "internationally-trained physician employee license" to
34 practice medicine and surgery to a physician when the Board has received satisfactory
35 verification of all of the following requirements:
36 (1) The applicant has been offered employment as a physician in a full-time
37 capacity at (i) a hospital that is located in North Carolina and licensed by the
38 State of North Carolina or (ii) a medical practice located in a rural county with
39 a population of less than 500 people per square mile, in North Carolina, where
40 a physician fully licensed by the State under this Chapter is physically
41 practicing on-site at the rural medical practice.
42 (2) The applicant has a current and active license in good standing to practice
43 medicine in a foreign country or had that type of license expire no more than
44 five years prior to submission of an application to the Board.
45 (3) The applicant previously completed 130 weeks of medical education at a
46 medical school listed in the World Dictionary of Medical Schools and is
47 eligible to be certified by the Educational Commission for Foreign Medical
48 Graduates and meets one of the following requirements:
49 a. The applicant has completed two years of postgraduate training in a
50 graduate medical education program approved by the applicant's
51 country of licensure.
Senate Bill 336-Second Edition Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 b. The applicant has actively practiced medicine in the applicant's
2 country of licensure for at least 10 years after graduation.
3 (4) The applicant has demonstrated competency to practice medicine in one of the
4 following ways:
5 a. Successfully passing each part of an examination listed in
6 G.S. 90-10.1.
7 b. Successfully passing each part of a nationally recognized standard
8 medical licensing examination from a country that is a member of the
9 International Association of Medical Regulatory Authorities that
10 meets all of the following requirements:
11 1. Tests for the ability to practice medicine.
12 2. Tests for medical knowledge, skills, and understanding of
13 clinical science essential for providing patient care, including
14 general practice, cardiology, internal medicine,
15 gastroenterology, hematology, nephrology, neurology,
16 pediatrics, psychiatry, pulmonology, obstetrics and
17 gynecology, radiology, rheumatology, urology, and surgery.
18 3. Tests for communication and interpersonal skills.
19 4. Includes an interactive testing component.
20 The examining body must provide verification in English directly to
21 the Board that the applicant has passed an examination meeting the
22 requirements of this sub-subdivision.
23 c. Receiving specialty board certification as approved by any of the
24 following:
25 1. The American Board of Medical Specialties.
26 2. The Bureau of Osteopathic Specialists of the American
27 Osteopathic Association.
28 3. The Royal College of Physicians and Surgeons of Canada.
29 4. Any other specialty board recognized pursuant to rules adopted
30 by the Board.
31 d. Submitting to a comprehensive assessment demonstrating clinical
32 competence by a program approved by the Board.
33 Alternatively, the Board may waive the requirements of this subdivision and
34 issue a temporary license and require the applicant to successfully pass the
35 Special Purpose Examination (SPEX) or Post-Licensure Assessment Systems
36 within one year.
37 (5) The applicant has not had a license revoked, suspended, restricted, denied, or
38 otherwise acted against in any jurisdiction and is the subject of no pending
39 investigations. For purposes of this subdivision, the licensing authority's
40 acceptance of a license to practice voluntarily relinquished by a licensee or
41 relinquished by stipulation, consent order, or other settlement in response to or
42 in anticipation of the filing of administrative charges against the licensee's
43 license, or an inactivation or voluntary surrender of a license while under
44 investigation, is deemed to be an action against a license to practice.
45 (6) The applicant does not have any convictions in any court involving moral
46 turpitude, or the violation of a law involving the practice of medicine, or a
47 conviction of a law substantially equivalent to a felony. The applicant shall submit
48 to, and the Board must receive, a background screening from the country in which
49 they are licensed.
50 (7) The applicant has practiced medicine for at least five years.
51 (8) The applicant is proficient in English.
Page 14 Senate Bill 336-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (9) The applicant is legally authorized to work in the United States. An applicant
2 may apply for an internationally-trained physician employee license before
3 receiving federal work authorization but may not begin employment with the
4 North Carolina hospital or rural medical practice until receiving legal work
5 authorization from the relevant federal agency.
6 (b) The holder of the internationally-trained physician employee license issued under this
7 section shall not practice medicine or surgery outside the confines of the North Carolina hospital
8 or rural medical practice, or its affiliate, by whose employment the holder was qualified to be
9 issued the license pursuant to subdivision (1) of subsection (a) of this section. A person who
10 violates this subsection shall be guilty of a Class 3 misdemeanor and, upon conviction, shall be
11 fined not more than five hundred dollars ($500.00) for each offense. The Board, at its discretion,
12 may revoke the special license after due notice is given to the holder of the certified physician
13 employee license.
14 (c) An internationally-trained physician employee license shall become inactive at the
15 time its holder does one or more of the following:
16 (1) Ceases to be employed in a full-time capacity by a North Carolina hospital or
17 medical practice meeting the criteria set forth in subdivision (1) of subsection
18 (a) of this section.
19 (2) Ceases to be employed at a medical practice located in a rural county or
20 practices if a physician licensed by the State under this Chapter is not
21 physically practicing on-site at the medical practice.
22 (3) Obtains any other license to practice medicine issued by the Board.
23 The Board shall retain jurisdiction over the holder of the inactive license.
24 (d) A physician with an internationally-trained physician employee license in good
25 standing shall automatically convert into a full license to practice medicine in North Carolina
26 after four years of active practice in North Carolina.
27 (e) The Board, in consultation with partner organizations as needed, shall collect
28 information necessary to evaluate the implementation and success of the pathway to licensure
29 established in this section, including at least the following:
30 (1) The number and types of inquiries from potential applicants.
31 (2) The number of applicants for provisional licensure.
32 (3) The applicant's licensing country or country where they were authorized to
33 practice medicine and, if different, country of education and training.
34 (4) The number of provisional licenses granted under this section.
35 (5) The number of provisional licenses denied under this section.
36 (6) The number of full and unrestricted licenses granted to applicants who
37 completed the pathway to licensure established in this section.
38 (7) The number of full and unrestricted license applications denied to applicants
39 who completed the pathway to licensure established in this section.
40 (8) The reasons for denial of applications for provisional and full unrestricted
41 licenses under this section.
42 (9) The number of complaints received regarding holders of a provisional license
43 issued under this section and the disciplinary actions taken, if any.
44 (10) The practice setting and specialty of applicants in their licensing country or
45 country of origin and as employed during their provisional and limited
46 licensure.
47 (11) The geographic area or rural/urban designation of where licensees practice
48 during provisional licensure and after the period of provisional licensure.
49 (12) The practice setting and specialty of internationally-trained physicians who
50 completed the pathway to licensure upon receiving a full and unrestricted
51 license.
Senate Bill 336-Second Edition Page 15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (f) Annually on or before December 1, the Board shall report the information collected
2 pursuant to subsection (e) of this section for the previous calendar year to the Joint Legislative
3 Oversight Committee on Health and Human Services."
4 SECTION 4. The North Carolina Medical Board (Board) shall adopt rules necessary
5 to issue an internationally-trained physician employee license. The Board may adopt a rule
6 establishing a time limit for the term of an internationally-trained physician employee license.
7 The Board may also adopt rules to implement Section 1 of this act.
8 SECTION 5. It is the intention of the General Assembly that the provisions of this
9 act shall be severable. If any provision of this act or its application to any person or circumstance
10 is held invalid, the remainder of the act or the application of the provision to other persons or
11 circumstances is not affected, including, but not limited to, the applicability of this act to the
12 provisions of future agreements subject to this act.
13 SECTION 6. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025.
